 this toppling. Zürcher carefully looks at the conditions within each region - economic, ethnic, religious, and political - to make sense of why some turned to violent conflict and some did not and what the future of the region might portend.This important volume provides both an overview of the region that is both up-to-date and comprehensive as well as an accessible understanding of the current scholarship on mobilization and violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aEthnic conflictzCaucasusvCase studies. 0aPolitical violencezCaucasusvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aArmenia.  aAzerbaijan.  aCaucasus.  aChechnya.  aDagestan.  aGeorgia.  aKarabakh.  aPost-Soviet.  aWars.  aaccount.  aareas.  acomparative.  afour.  aincluding.  alooking.  aorganized.  aregion.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814797440423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814797440/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK